Chapter-6
Biodiversity and its Conservation
Answer the following
Q2. How can you say that forests are biosphere reserves?
Give reasons.
A. 1. Biosphere reserve is an area inhabited by living
organisms.
2. Forests are natural habitats for many types of plants (flora)
and animals (fauna).
3. Plants are primary producers providing food to all the living
organisms on earth.
4. Every part of the plant and animal body is used by man in
their daily life.
5. We get cereals, pulses, oil, seeds, timber and fibres from
plants.
6. In addition to these products resins, fruits, vegetables etc. are
obtained from plants.
7. Primitive man used to obtain his food by hunting animals in
the forests.
8. Variety of animals live in the forests. Various products from
them are meat, milk, fur and skin.
9. Man also uses some of the plant products.
10. Thus we can say that forests are biosphere reserves.

Q3. What do you understand by the terms a) extinct b)
endangered c) endemic. Give examples.
A. Extinct :-
We find that many animals that were found earlier are not
found now. When animals vanish forever from the earth, it is
said that the species have become extinct.
Eg:- Dinosaurs, Dodo birds etc.
Endangered :-
We notice that a few animals are slowly disappearing from
our surroundings . Vanishing means, it is a warning signal for
the animals who have declined rapidly and may be wiped of
in our future. Such animals are called endangered species.
Eg:- Lion, tiger, panda etc.
Endemic species :-
Some species of plants and animals are only restricted to
particular area of a country are called endemic species.
Eg:- Kiwi, White tiger, Peacock , anteater, Blue jay etc.

Q4. What is the scientific reason behind birds migration?
A. 1.Sometimes some birds live in the same habitat through
out the year.
2.Other birds which don't have permanent nestlings and join
small flocks and move from one region to the other for food
and shelter called as migration and such birds are called
as migratory birds.
3. Birds migrate mainly for :-
a) nestling
b) food
c) suitable conditions to live
d) reproduction
Therefore, scientifically birds migrate to survive in
unsustainable conditions.

Q7. Nowadays we find animals like leopards and bears
intruding into our living places. What may be the reason
for this?
A. 1.Forests are the living places for wild animals. Animals
can get plenty of shelter from the shade of the trees and
they feel secured in the forests.
2. People are so greedy that they cut down the forest area for
logging of wood, to increase agriculture and human habitat.
3. Due to deforestation, now-a- days animals like leopards and
bears lose their shelter and food.
4. To satisfy their hunger and to keep themselves alive they
are intruding into our living places.
5. To escape from hunters and climatic conditions due to
deforestation is one more reason for animals to come into
our living places.

Q8. Make a list of animals /birds seen now and 30 years
ago. Take the help of your elders. Write few reasons for
their disappearance.
A. 1. List of animals and birds :-
Animals like Lions, tigers, jackals, deer, hyena, squirrels etc.
and birds like crow, peacock, mynah, flamingo, kingfisher etc.
2. Endangered species and animals of India :-
Lion, vulture, tiger , Spotted deer, Black spider monkey,
Single horned rhino, Red fox, Wild cat, Loris, Cycas,
Rauwolfia serpentina, Nepenthes, Sandal wood tree etc.
3.There are species of mammals such as Indian cheetah, Javan
Rhinoceros and birds like pink headed duck and Himalayan
quail have become extinct.
4. Warbler, a bird found in Rampur of Himachal Pradesh was
rediscovered after 139 years in Thailand.
5. Based on a case study we find that many animals that were
found earlier are not found now.
Reasons for their disappearance:
1. Hunting animals for food, pleasure, feeding cattle has made
animals to become extinct.
2. Exploitation of land and forest resources by humans.
3. Pollution of air, water and soil also leads to extinction of
plants and animals.

Q13. Where do you find most of the biodiversity on the
earth?
A. 1.In areas with sufficient amount of water, a wide variety
of plants ranging from grasses to tall trees are seen.
2. Most of the forests are seen in these areas.
3. As there is sufficient vegetation, there will be a large
number of herbivorous animals. Carnivorous animals
which feed on the herbivores are also found in these
regions.
4. Generally there is an increase in biodiversity from poles to
tropics. These localities at lower altitudes have more
species than the localities at higher altitudes.
5. Ultimate factor is greater mean temperature at the equator.
__________________________________________________
Q14. What do you understand by biodiversity? How can
you say variations are present in them?
A. 1.The variety and variability seen in plants and animals is
called biodiversity.
2. The whole world has a variety of living organisms both
visible and invisible.
Eg:- Different micro-organisms like algae, fungi, bacteria,
virus, micro-arthropods are found around us. We see
diversity in these organisms also. There are number of
species belonging to each group.
3. There are different varieties of plants like grass, herbs,
shrubs, creepers and trees. In these again we find
variation in their height, colour, size of flowers and
fruits.
4. Similarly we find variations among animals in the colour ,
fur, nails, claws and hooves etc.
5. In birds we can see variations in their feathers, feet, crown,
beak and tail.
6. All human beings belong to same genus but there is
variation in their hand, fingers, toes, nails, shape, hair
and height.
7. We can find variations in the texture of skin like dry, oily,
smooth and rough.
8. Whether they are twins also we can find variations among
them.

Q15. Most of our biodiversity is being lost due to human
activities. Suggest a few ways to protect them.
A. Most of our bio-diversity is being lost due to human
activities like logging of wood, increased agriculture,
human habitation, pollution etc. Man has realized the
mistake before it was too late. Government of India also
realized the importance of wild life in the country and
WILD LIFE ACT was passed in 1972. Government of
India initiated several programmes to preserve wild life in
the country.
Efforts towards conservation:-
1. Activity leading to deforestation has been declared as
illegal activities and severe punishments have been imposed.
2. Poaching of birds and hunting their eggs are prohibited.
3. Usage of pesticides should be minimized, usage of
biological control methods of pests should be maintained.
4. Efforts to be made to substitute chemical fertilizers with
more bio-fertilizers.
5. Pollution from the industries should be reduced.
6. Automobiles should be designed to reduce pollution.
7. Reforestation programme will be conducted.
8. Gardens, parks, zoo's should be developed.
9. National parks, wild life sanctuaries where wild life is
protected have been created.
10. Collection , marketing and selling of forest products such
as sandalwood, ivory by private parties is banned and is taken
up by the government.
11. Construction of cell towers which produce radiation,
should be at greater height, so that it is not reachable to birds.
Q17. Prepare an essay to give a talk on biodiversity and
conservation.
A. 1. The existence of biodiversity in nature teaches us that
every plant and animal whether useful or not has the
right to exist on the earth.
2. Every organism is a part of our ecosystem. Loss of any
organism endemic or otherwise affects the food chain
and food web of that ecosystem, which has impact on
the biodiversity of the world.
3. Hence if we want to protect the biodiversity on our
planet, first we must be a part of conservation and then
make others aware of it because today we see extinction
of some species but tomorrow it could be our species.
4. Conserving the biodiversity in a wider perspective is
utilizing the forest resources judiciously without
affecting the ecosystems so that we can have a
sustainable development in the forests and the
biodiversity can be conserved for future generations.
5. Nature is for humans need, not for his greed. If we protect
nature, it protects us.

Q18.Rani said conservation of biodiversity starts from our
home. Is she correct? How do you support her? What will
be your action for this?
A. 1. We live in houses that protect us from heat, cold, rain
etc.
2. We grow plants that give us fresh air, vegetables and
shade.
3. We domesticate animals and birds besides that, we find
cockroaches, ants, spiders living with us.
4. Therefore, we can say that our house is a habitat.
5. Different kinds of birds and animals such as pigeons,
crows, goats and cows with us.
6. The plants and animals are well taken care of and we put
an effort to protect them from calamities. This is
conservation of bio-diversity.
7. If we protect the nature around us and conserve it the
people living in houses will be healthy.
8. Hence, we can say that bio-diversity at our houses helps to
develop aesthetic values in children.
Q19. When we take steps towards conserving the tiger,
what are the other things that have to be considered?
A. 1. When we take steps towards conserving the tiger we
have to conserve the other flora and fauna related to the
tiger.
2. If a tiger has to be saved, its food web should be
protected.
3. The tiger depends for food on deer and many other
herbivores.
4. If the tiger disappears, the deer and other herbivores
population will increase and that would effect the flora of
the area.
5. All organisms in nature influence each other in some way
or the other. So we need to protect all of them.
